article.headline: New Hampshire 65, Dartmouth 61
article.story: HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Jermaine Anderson scored a game-high 21 points and was 7-for-7 from the free throw line in the final 37 seconds as New Hampshire held off a late Dartmouth rally to claim a 65-61 victory Tuesday night. Blagoj Janev added 15 points while Radar Onguetou had 11 rebounds and nine points for New Hampshire (6-12). Dartmouth (6-9) got 18 points from Leon Pattman, 16 points and 12 rebounds from Alex Barnett and 13 points from DeVon Mosley. New Hampshire shot 66.7 percent from the field and was 6-of-9 from outside the arc. The Wildcats led at halftime, 41-28. New Hampshire made its first four shots of the second half to build its biggest lead of the game, 49-28. Dartmouth used a 10-2 burst to make it 51-38 midway through the second half. With the New Hampshire lead at 55-40 and 6 minutes remaining, Dartmouth hit five consecutive shots, including three 3-pointers by Mosley and another by Pattman, to pull within 58-54 with 2:10 left. After a UNH turnover, Pattman's reverse layup to make it a two-point game with 1:14 left. Pattman's 3-pointer with 8 seconds remaining made it 63-61 before Anderson sealed the UNH win by making two free throws.
